<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="853" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d853">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.622a/134</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The German Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BJHACV1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bernstorff</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">J. Nr. A 3485</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-13"><hi rend="italic">May 13,
                                        1916</hi></date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received May
                                    16</hi>.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: In reply to your kind
                            note No. 1919<note n="1" xml:id="d853fn1">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_640">p.
                                640</ref>.</note> of the 4th of this month I have the honor to say
                            that the German subjects taken from the S. S. <hi rend="italic">China</hi> do not belong to the German military organization.</p>
                        <p>The German subject Streckfuss, to be sure, was a temporary member of the
                            guard of the Imperial Legation at Peking and the German subject E. Klein
                            was for a while employed as unarmed watchman in the city of Tsingtau,
                            but both had been for some time before discharged from any military
                            service liability. They are non-combatants arid both being over 48 years
                            old are no longer subject to military duty under the law of Germany.</p>
                        <p>So far as known, the Austro-Hungarian and Turkish subjects taken from the
                            ship are likewise civilians. Yet I would leave it with your excellency
                            to apply to Austro-Hungarian and Turkish representatives on their
                            account.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BJHACV1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">J. Bernstorff</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>